{{For|the mass formula of quadratic forms|Smith–Minkowski–Siegel mass formula}}
{{Unreferenced|date=October 2008}}

A '''mass formula''' is an [[equation]] or set of equations in [[physics]] which attempts to predict the [[mass]] or mass ratios of the [[subatomic particles]]. 

An important step in high energy physics was the discovery of the [[Gell-Mann–Okubo mass formula]] predicting relationships between masses of the members of [[Special_unitary_group#SU.283.29|SU(3)]] [[Quark model|multiplets]].

The development of an accurate mass formula is one of several fundamental aspects to developing a working [[theory of everything]], which is expected to overcome the incompatibilities between current [[classical physics|classical]] and [[quantum physics]] theories.

There are currently no universal mass formulae which are generally accepted as correct by the mainstream physics community, however several versions of potential mass formulae have been presented and are currently being explored by some (largely amateur) physics theorists.{{fact|date=March 2013}}

